  <div class="bg-warning">
    <h3>Here's a time line of Dr. Stella Ameyo Adadevoh's life:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>1956</strong>: born in Lagos Nigeria.</li>
      <li><strong>1961</strong>: began her academic career at Mainland Preparatory Primary School in Yaba, Lagos.</li>
      <li><strong>1962</strong>: Ameyoâ€™s parents temporarily relocated to Boston, Massachusetts in the United States of America where Ameyo spent two years in school.</li>
      <li><strong>1964</strong>: she and her family returned to Nigeria.</li>
      <li><strong>1968</strong>: She began secondary school at Queens School Ibadan, Nigeria.</li>
      <li><strong>1974</strong>: finished secondary school with a distinction of honors in her West African Examinations Council (WAEC) Exams.</li>
      <li><strong>1980</strong>: at the age of 24, Ameyo qualified as a medical doctor with a Bachelor of Medicine/Bachelor of Surgery (MBBS) degree from the University of Lagos College of Medicine.</li>
      <li><strong>1982</strong>: she finished a one year mandatory housemanship at Lagos University Teaching Hospital and subsequently completed her National Youth Service Corps assignment at The Eti-Osa Health Centre in Lagos, Nigeria.</li>
      <li><strong>1983-1988</strong>: Her professional career began with a residency at Lagos University Teaching Hospital</li>
      <li><strong>1986</strong>: Ameyo married Afolabi Emmanuel Cardoso</li>
      <li><strong>1991</strong>: she earned a prestigious British Council Scholarship to continue her education abroad.</li>
      <li><strong>On 4 August 2014</strong>: he is credited with having curbed a wider spread of the Ebola virus in Nigeria by placing the patient zero, Patrick Sawyer, in quarantine despite pressures from the Liberian Government.</li>
      <li><strong>On 19th August 2014</strong>: Ameyo went to rest with the Lord after being confirm that she had tested positive for Ebola virus disease.</li>
    </ul></div>
